# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-app-runner
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] Autoscaling differs from having a fixed daily, weekly, or yearly cycle of server use in that it is responsive to actual usage patterns, and thus reduces the potential downside of having too few or too many servers for the traffic load.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] For instance, if traffic is usually lower at midnight, then a static scaling solution might schedule some servers to sleep at night, but this might result in downtime on a night where people happen to use the Internet more (for instance, due to a viral news event).
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] Autoscaling, on the other hand, can handle unexpected traffic spikes better.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] In the list below, we use the terminology used by Amazon Web Services (AWS).
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] However, alternative names are noted and terminology that is specific to the names of Amazon services is not used for the names.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] Amazon Web Services launched the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) service in August 2006, that allowed developers to programmatically create and terminate instances (machines).
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] At the time of initial launch, AWS did not offer autoscaling, but the ability to programmatically create and terminate instances gave developers the flexibility to write their own code for autoscaling.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] Third-party autoscaling software for AWS began appearing around April 2008.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] These included tools by Scalr and RightScale.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] RightScale was used by Animoto, which was able to handle Facebook traffic by adopting autoscaling.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] On May 18, 2009, Amazon launched its own autoscaling feature along with Elastic Load Balancing, as part of Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] Autoscaling is now an integral component of Amazon's EC2 offering.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] Autoscaling on Amazon Web Services is done through a web browser or the command line tool.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] In May 2016 Autoscaling was also offered in AWS ECS Service.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] On-demand video provider Netflix documented their use of autoscaling with Amazon Web Services to meet their highly variable consumer needs.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] They found that aggressive scaling up and delayed and cautious scaling down served their goals of uptime and responsiveness best.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] In an article for *TechCrunch*, Zev Laderman, the co-founder and CEO of Newvem, a service that helps optimize AWS cloud infrastructure, recommended that startups use autoscaling in order to keep their Amazon Web Services costs low.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] Various best practice guides for AWS use suggest using its autoscaling feature even in cases where the load is not variable.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] Netflix's internal best practices require every instance to be in an autoscaling group, and its conformity monkey terminates any instance not in an autoscaling group in order to enforce this best practice.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] On June 27, 2013, Microsoft announced that it was adding autoscaling support to its Windows Azure cloud computing platform.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] Documentation for the feature is available on the Microsoft Developer Network.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] Oracle Cloud Platform allows server instances to automatically scale a cluster in or out by defining an auto-scaling rule.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] These rules are based on CPU and/or memory utilization and determine when to add or remove nodes.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] On November 17, 2014, the Google Compute Engine announced a public beta of its autoscaling feature for use in Google Cloud Platform applications.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] As of March 2015, the autoscaling tool is still in Beta.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] In a blog post in August 2014, a Facebook engineer disclosed that the company had started using autoscaling to bring down its energy costs.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] The blog post reported a 27% decline in energy use for low traffic hours (around midnight) and a 10-15% decline in energy use over the typical 24-hour cycle.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] Autoscaling by default uses *reactive* decision approach for dealing with traffic scaling: scaling only happens in response to real-time changes in metrics.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] In some cases, particularly when the changes occur very quickly, this reactive approach to scaling is insufficient.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] Two other kinds of autoscaling decision approaches are described below.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] This is an approach to autoscaling where changes are made to the minimum size, maximum size, or desired capacity of the autoscaling group at specific times of day.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] Scheduled scaling is useful, for instance, if there is a known traffic load increase or decrease at specific times of the day, but the change is too sudden for reactive approach based autoscaling to respond fast enough.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] AWS autoscaling groups support scheduled scaling.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] This approach to autoscaling uses predictive analytics.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] The idea is to combine recent usage trends with historical usage data as well as other kinds of data to predict usage in the future, and autoscale based on these predictions.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] For parts of their infrastructure and specific workloads, Netflix found that Scryer, their predictive analytics engine, gave better results than Amazon's reactive autoscaling approach.
[src:aws-app-runner/autoscaling] On November 20, 2018, AWS announced that predictive scaling would be available as part of its autoscaling offering.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] AWS App Runner has been used by various companies to streamline the deployment of their web applications and APIs.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] Some notable customers include Classmethod, Hubble, and Velo by Wix.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] These companies have leveraged App Runner to achieve faster time-to-market, improved developer productivity, and simplified application development processes.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] The AWS Cloud Development Kit (AWS CDK) introduced support for AWS App Runner in August 2021, enabling developers to define and deploy App Runner services using the AWS CDK.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] This streamlines the application development and deployment process by automating the creation of App Runner services, managing them through Infrastructure as Code (IaC), and using familiar programming languages to define their infrastructure.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] The AWS CDK offers L1 support for AWS App Runner, corresponding to the low-level constructs.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] Additionally, an experimental L2 construct library, @aws-cdk/aws-apprunner-alpha, is available in preview, offering a more abstracted and developer-friendly approach.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] Although AWS App Runner can simplify the deployment of containerized applications, certain limitations should be considered when evaluating its suitability for specific use cases.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] It currently only support linux containers.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] Furthermore, App Runner does not offer a "scale to zero" option like Google Cloud Run and lacks support for AWS CodeCommit as a code-based service repository.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] AWS App Runner offers deployment and management for containerized applications.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] It can be compared to other AWS services and similar offerings from other cloud providers, such as AWS Elastic Beanstalk, AWS Copilot, and Google Cloud Run.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] AWS Elastic Beanstalk is another service that automates the deployment of applications.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] However, it provides more control over the infrastructure once deployed, which can be a necessity in some cases but also introduces the potential for unmanaged changes.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] In contrast, App Runner is entirely managed, minimizing administrative overhead.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] AWS Copilot, released as a command-line tool to simplify ECS deployments, offers a compelling niche but initially lacked the ability to scale.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] AWS Copilot has since released version 1.7.0, which natively supports App Runner and bridges the gap between the two services.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] Google Cloud Run is a similar service offered by Google Cloud Platform (GCP) that allows developers to deploy and manage containerized applications.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] One significant difference between App Runner and Google Cloud Run is that the latter offers the option to "scale to zero," reducing costs for infrequently accessed applications.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] App Runner currently lacks this feature, resulting in higher costs for such applications.
[src:aws-app-runner/aws-app-runner] Microsoft released a similar product called Azure Container Apps.
[src:aws-app-runner/container-virtualization] In software engineering, **containerization** is operating-system-level virtualization or application-level virtualization over multiple resources so that software applications can run in isolated user spaces called *containers* in any cloud or non-cloud environment, regardless of type or vendor.
[src:aws-app-runner/container-virtualization] The term "container" has different meanings in different contexts, and it is important to ensure that the intended definition aligns with the audience's understanding.
[src:aws-app-runner/container-virtualization] Each *container* is basically a fully functional and portable cloud or non-cloud computing environment surrounding the application and keeping it independent of other environments running in parallel.
[src:aws-app-runner/container-virtualization] Individually, each container simulates a different software application and runs isolated processes by bundling related configuration files, libraries and dependencies.
[src:aws-app-runner/container-virtualization] But, collectively, multiple containers share a common operating system kernel (OS).
[src:aws-app-runner/container-virtualization] In recent times, containerization technology has been widely adopted by cloud computing platforms like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, and IBM Cloud.
[src:aws-app-runner/container-virtualization] Containerization has also been pursued by the U.S.
[src:aws-app-runner/container-virtualization] Department of Defense as a way of more rapidly developing and fielding software updates, with first application in its F-22 air superiority fighter.
[src:aws-app-runner/container-virtualization] Container orchestration or container management is mostly used in the context of application containers.
[src:aws-app-runner/container-virtualization] Implementations providing such orchestration include Kubernetes and Docker swarm.
[src:aws-app-runner/container-virtualization] This includes functionality to create a cluster, to upgrade the software or repair it, balance the load between existing instances, scale by starting or stopping instances to adapt to the number of users, to log activities and monitor produced logs or the application itself by querying sensors.
[src:aws-app-runner/container-virtualization] Open-source implementations of such software include OKD and Rancher.
[src:aws-app-runner/container-virtualization] Quite a number of companies provide container cluster management as a managed service, like Alibaba, Amazon, Google, and Microsoft.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:aws-app-runner/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:aws-app-runner/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] A **web application** (or **web app**) is application software that is created with web technologies and runs via a web browser.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Web applications emerged during the late 1990s and allowed for the server to dynamically build a response to the request, in contrast to static web pages.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Web applications are commonly distributed via a web server.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] There are several different tier systems that web applications use to communicate between the web browsers, the client interface, and server data.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Each system has its own uses as they function in different ways.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] However, there are many security risks that developers must be aware of during development; proper measures to protect user data are vital.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Web applications are often constructed with the use of a web application framework.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Single-page applications (SPAs) and progressive web apps (PWAs) are two architectural approaches to creating web applications that provide a user experience similar to native apps, including features such as smooth navigation, offline support, and faster interactions.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Modern browsers such as Chrome offer sandboxing for every browser tab which improves security and restricts access to local resources.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] No software installation is required as the app runs within the browser which reduces the need for managing software installations.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] With the use of remote cloud services, customers do not need to manage servers as that can be left to the developer and the cloud service and can use the software with a relatively low power, low-resource PC such as a thin client.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] The source code of the application can stay the same across operating systems and devices of users with the use of responsive web design, since it only needs to be compatible with web browsers which adhere to web standards, making the code highly portable and saving on development time.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Numerous JavaScript frameworks and CSS frameworks facilitate development.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] The concept of a "web application" was first introduced in the Java language in the Servlet Specification version 2.2, which was released in 1999.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] At that time, both JavaScript and XML had already been developed, but the XMLHttpRequest object had only been recently introduced on Internet Explorer 5 as an ActiveX object.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Beginning around the early 2000s, applications such as "Myspace (2003), Gmail (2004), Digg (2004), [and] Google Maps (2005)," started to make their client sides more and more interactive.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] A web page script is able to contact the server for storing/retrieving data without downloading an entire web page.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] The practice became known as Ajax in 2005.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Eventually this was replaced by web APIs using JSON, accessed via JavaScript asynchronously on the client side.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] In earlier computing models like client-server, the processing load for the application was shared between code on the server and code installed on each client locally.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] In other words, an application had its own pre-compiled client program which served as its user interface and had to be separately installed on each user's personal computer.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] An upgrade to the server-side code of the application would typically also require an upgrade to the client-side code installed on each user workstation, adding to the support cost and decreasing productivity.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Additionally, both the client and server components of the application were bound tightly to a particular computer architecture and operating system, which made porting them to other systems prohibitively expensive for all but the largest applications.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Later, in 1995, Netscape introduced the client-side scripting language called JavaScript, which allowed programmers to add dynamic elements to the user interface that ran on the client side.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Essentially, instead of sending data to the server in order to generate an entire web page, the embedded scripts of the downloaded page can perform various tasks such as input validation or showing/hiding parts of the page.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Traditional PC applications are typically single-tiered, residing solely on the client machine.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] In contrast, web applications inherently facilitate a multi-tiered architecture.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Though many variations are possible, the most common structure is the three-tiered application.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] In its most common form, the three tiers are called *presentation*, *application* and *storage*.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] The first tier, presentation, refers to a web browser itself.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] The second tier refers to any engine using dynamic web content technology (such as ASP, CGI, ColdFusion, Dart, JSP/Java, Node.js, PHP, Python or Ruby on Rails).
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] The third tier refers to a database that stores data and determines the structure of a user interface.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Essentially, when using the three-tiered system, the web browser sends requests to the engine, which then services them by making queries and updates against the database and generates a user interface.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] The 3-tier solution may fall short when dealing with more complex applications, and may need to be replaced with the n-tiered approach; the greatest benefit of which is how business logic (which resides on the application tier) is broken down into a more fine-grained model.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Another benefit would be to add an integration tier, which separates the data tier and provides an easy-to-use interface to access the data.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] For example, the client data would be accessed by calling a "list_clients()" function instead of making an SQL query directly against the client table on the database.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] This allows the underlying database to be replaced without making any change to the other tiers.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] There are some who view a web application as a two-tier architecture.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] This can be a "smart" client that performs all the work and queries a "dumb" server, or a "dumb" client that relies on a "smart" server.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] The client would handle the presentation tier, the server would have the database (storage tier), and the business logic (application tier) would be on one of them or on both.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] While this increases the scalability of the applications and separates the display and the database, it still does not allow for true specialization of layers, so most applications will outgrow this model.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Security breaches on these kinds of applications are a major concern because it can involve both enterprise information and private customer data.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Protecting these assets is an important part of any web application, and there are some key operational areas that must be included in the development process.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] This includes processes for authentication, authorization, asset handling, input, and logging and auditing.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Building security into the applications from the beginning is sometimes more effective and less disruptive in the long run.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] Writing web applications is simplified with the use of web application frameworks.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] These frameworks facilitate rapid application development by allowing a development team to focus on the parts of their application which are unique to their goals without having to resolve common development issues such as user management.
[src:aws-app-runner/web-application] In addition, there is potential for the development of applications on Internet operating systems, although currently there are not many viable platforms that fit this model.
